[3] Taiwan response - CDC Taiwan
Date: 25 Apr 2004
From: Peter Chang MD <wpc94@yahoo.com>
Source: CDC Taiwan 23 Apr 2004 [edited]
<http://www.cdc.gov.tw/sarsen/>
<http://203.65.72.83/En/ITC/ShowPublication.ASP?RecNo=959>

Taiwan SARS Responsive Level Escalated to Level A
------------------------------------------------
In response to 2 suspected SARS cases reported in China, Taiwan Department
of Health has announced today that starting 24 Apr 2004, the SARS
responsive level will be escalated from "SARS and other emerging infectious
diseases preparedness phase" to level A, which is defined as when the 1st
confirmed case of SARS is reported globally.
According to the press releases from WHO and Department of Health, Hong
Kong, 2 suspected SARS cases in Beijing and Anhui respectively have been
reported. Please refer to <http://www.who.int/csr/don/2004_04_22/en/> and
<http://www.info.gov.hk/dh/new/index.htm> for further information.
Therefore, the Department of Health has resumed "SARS control and
prevention committee" meetings to improve our level of response to SARS.
The following precautionary measures have been adopted:
1. All incoming passengers are required to fill in the "SARS and other
communicable diseases survey form" and to have their body temperature taken
by an infrared thermal camera.
2. Tourists or businessmen who departed from Beijing and Anhui are required
to fill a "Tourists from Beijing and Anhui Survey Form" for follow-up.
3. Self-health management required for incoming tourists or businessmen who
departed from China, Hong Kong and Macau.
Although no suspected SARS case has been identified in Taiwan, Taiwan CDC
would like to remind the public to keep good personal hygiene (e.g.
hand-washing, temperature monitoring) as well as to avoid going to work
and/or school when fever develops to prevent future re-emergence of SARS.
[From a newswire also submitted by Dr. Chang:
<http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2004/04/24/2003137874>
The Taiwan CDC yesterday raised its SARS response level to A from 0. Level
0 indicates that there are no cases of SARS worldwide, level A the
detection of SARS cases in other nations, level B the detection of SARS in
Taiwan, and level C, numerous cases of SARS in Taiwan.
As a result of the move, the CDC began increasing border surveillance
efforts at midnight last night [23 Apr 2004]. Su explained that travelers
to Taiwan from Beijing or Anhui Province would be required to fill out
forms confirming their health. They will also be required to conduct
personal health management, which would include keeping records of daily
temperature readings. CDC officials will make follow-up phone calls for 10
days to verify health conditions. - Mod.MPP]
--
Peter Chang, MD, MPH, ScD
Professor and liaison officer to WHO
<wpc94@yahoo.com>
